INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6decd956-727a-4961-aec7-4daa2477129f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$webpack Environment Variables — DefinePlugin, dotenv, and Build-Time vs Runtime$escape$,
  $escape$webpack has no native `.env` support — you wire it up yourself. The standard approach combines `dotenv` with `DefinePlugin`: parse your `.env` file in `webpack.config.js`, then use `DefinePlugin` to statically replace identifiers at compile time. Every `process.env.API_URL` reference gets inlined as a string literal in the bundle — it's a text substitution, not a real Node.js environment lookup. That distinction matters: values are baked in at build time, so shipping one bundle to multiple environments (staging/prod) requires separate builds or a runtime injection strategy.

For runtime config, skip `DefinePlugin` entirely. Serve a `config.js` from your CDN or server that sets `window.__ENV__`, load it via a `<script>` tag before your bundle, and read from `window.__ENV__` in app code. This lets ops teams change URLs without rebuilding.

Never pass secrets through `DefinePlugin` — anything inlined becomes readable in the bundle. Use it only for public, environment-specific constants like API base URLs or feature flags.$escape$,
  $escape$// webpack.config.js
const path = require('path');
const webpack = require('webpack');
const dotenv = require('dotenv');

const env = dotenv.config({ path: `.env.${process.env.NODE_ENV}` }).parsed ?? {};

const envKeys = Object.fromEntries(
  Object.entries(env).map(([key, val]) => [`process.env.${key}`, JSON.stringify(val)])
);

module.exports = {
  plugins: [
    new webpack.DefinePlugin(envKeys),
  ],
};$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
