INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'efe8c292-6907-4a56-8d86-c660cb1590fc',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$webpack Config Sharing, Base Extension, and CI Filesystem Caching$escape$,
  $escape$webpack config sharing typically relies on `webpack-merge`. Split your setup into `webpack.common.js`, `webpack.dev.js`, and `webpack.prod.js`. Each environment file calls `merge(common, envSpecific)` — layering in `devServer`, `devtool`, or `TerserPlugin` without duplicating entry points or `resolve.alias` definitions.

For CI build caching, webpack 5's built-in `cache` option with `type: 'filesystem'` serializes the module graph to disk between runs. Set `cache.buildDependencies.config` pointing to all config files — webpack auto-invalidates the cache when any of them change. On GitHub Actions, cache the `.cache/webpack` directory keyed on a hash of `package-lock.json` plus your config files. A warmed cache can cut incremental CI builds from 3–4 minutes to under 30 seconds on mid-sized apps.

One sharp edge: `cache.name` defaults to the webpack `mode`, so dev and prod caches won't collide. But if you run multiple webpack configs in the same repo — a library build alongside an app build — set explicit `cache.name` values per config to prevent cross-contamination of the serialized module graph.$escape$,
  $escape$// webpack.prod.js
const { merge } = require('webpack-merge');
const common = require('./webpack.common.js');

module.exports = merge(common, {
  mode: 'production',
  devtool: 'source-map',
  cache: {
    type: 'filesystem',
    cacheDirectory: path.resolve(__dirname, '.cache/webpack'),
    buildDependencies: {
      config: [__filename, path.resolve(__dirname, 'webpack.common.js')],
    },
    name: 'prod-cache',
  },
});$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
